<TITLE> Brazil needs new ministry to fight crime - candidate </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SAO PAULO, Apr 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Opposition candidate Jose Serra said on Monday that he would create a ministry of public security to clean up Brazil's crime-ridden streets if he is elected president in October. The pledge was a rare moment of revelation for the veteran politician, who has been cagey about what shape his administration could take. "If I am president, I'll create a ministry of public security," Serra, who recently stepped down as governor of Sao Paulo state to run for president, said in a television interview broadcast live. Violent crime has become a persistent problem in Brazil, that has troubled the current president, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, and his predecessors. But as Brazil has sought to broaden its regional and world influence, including a bid for a permanent spot on the U.N. Security Council, the pervasiveness of crime here has garnered more international attention. The country is scheduled to host the soccer World Cup in 2014. Two years later, the Olympic Games will be held in Rio de Janeiro, one of Brazil's most violent cities. Serra, of the centrist Brazilian Social Democracy Party, has been working to soften his image as cold and aloof ahead of the elections. His main rival in the race is Dilma Rousseff of the ruling Workers' Party, hand-picked as a candidate by the wildly popular Lula. At the conclusion of the TV interview on Monday, an unusually jolly Serra sang part of the classic bossa nova song "Chega de Saudade," which was recorded in English as "No More Blues." It was the kind of gesture that the rough-and-ready Lula, with his Midas touch among voters, has often indulged in hims
